result.execSummary:
The defendant Alonso Nmi Corral was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Alonso Nmi Corral is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Alonso Nmi Corral was found guilty of Attempt 1st-Degree Intentional Homicide [Modifiers: Repeater, Use of a Dangerous Weapon], a class B felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.01(1)(a).
  • Alonso Nmi Corral was found guilty of 1st-Degree Recklessly Endangering Safety [Modifiers: Repeater, Use of a Dangerous Weapon], a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.30(1).
  • Alonso Nmi Corral was found guilty of 1st-Degree Recklessly Endangering Safety [Modifiers: Repeater, Use of a Dangerous Weapon], a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.30(1).
  • Alonso Nmi Corral was found guilty of 1st-Degree Recklessly Endangering Safety [Modifiers: Repeater, Use of a Dangerous Weapon], a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.30(1).
  • Alonso Nmi Corral was found guilty of Endanger Safety/Reckless Use of Firearm [Modifiers: Repeater], a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.20(2)(a).
  • Alonso Nmi Corral was found guilty of Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor [Modifiers: Repeater], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).

Defendant Alonso Nmi Corral in court, in custody, with attorney Anthony D Cotton and Christopher Ehrfurth.   Ted S. Szczupakiewicz and Bryan Bayer appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court officer, Detective Casey, appeared.  Case called for Day 3 of Jury trial at 8:36.  Defense renews motion to dismiss Count 5.  Court denies motion.  Jurors recalled at 8:40.  Court reads jury instructions.  Closing arguments by the State.  Closing arguments by the Defense.  Jurors excused at 9:50.  Discussion regarding closing statements of defense regarding Detective Casey.  Court takse recess at 9:53.  Trial resumed at 10:01.  Court will allow State to address statements of the defense regarding Detective Casey.  Jurors recalled at 10:11.  Rebuttal by the State.  Court reads final jury instructions.  Civilian baliff sworn in.  2 alternate jurors selected.  Jurors excused to deliberate at 10:34.  Alternates given instructions and excused by the court at 10:43.  Parties discuss exhibits.  Exhibits 1-4, 6-9, and 12-18 may go into the jury room if requested.  Jury submits a question at 11:12 which is marked at Court's Exhibit 1.  Trial resumed at 11:23.  All parties are present with the exception of Attorney Cotton.  Court will send a note to the jurors in response to their questions which will be marked as Court's Exhibit 2.  Court takes recess at 11:25.  Trial resumed at 1:34.  Parties advised jurors reached a verdict at 1:15.  Jurors recalled at 1:35.  Jurors find defendant guilty in all 6 Counts.  Court polls jurors.  Jurors discharged at 1:41.  State moves for Judgment on the verdicts.  Defense moves for Judgment notwithstanding the verdicts.  Court grants the motion of the State and finds the defendant guilty as to all 6 counts.  Court orders bail revoked.  Court orders Presentence Investigation to be completed and report filed within 30 days.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for January 26, 2015 at 03:00 pm.

Defendant Alonso Nmi Corral in court, in custody, with attorney Anthony D Cotton and Christopher Ehrfurth.   Ted S. Szczupakiewicz and Bryan Bayer appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court officer, Detective Casey in court.  Case called at 8:33 for Day 2 of Jury trial.  State calls D.J. to the stand.  D.J. sworn in and testified on direct examination, cross examination and redirect.  Exhibits 6 and 7 marked.  Jurors excused at 9:35.  Court memorializes sidebar.  Tables will be repositioned to help with the sightlines.  Court takes recess at 9:38.  Trial resumed and jurors recalled at 9:38.  State calls J.G. to the stand.  J.G. sworn in and testified on direct examination, cross examination and redirect.  Defense requests subpoena for J.G. be maintained at this time.  State calls ID Specialist David Platta to the stand.  Specialist Platta sworn in and testified on direct examination.  Jurors excused and court takes recess at 10:59.  Trial resumed and jurors recalled at 11:14. Specialist Platta testified on cross examination, redirect and recross.  Jurors excused at 11:34.  Discussion regarding the bail jumping charge.  Parties will draft a stipulation as to this matter.  Court orders the original bond from 13CM1921 be substituted with a certified copy in that file so the original may be marked as an exhibit in this case.  Clerk to notify Attorney Benedict to be available for court at 1:15 today.  Jurors recalled at 11:44.  Court advises jurors tha the state intends to rest after the lunch break.  Jurors excused at 11:47.  State offers exhibits 1-4 and 6-17.  All State's exhibits received by the court.  Defense offers exhibit 5.  State objects.  Court receives exhibit 5 over the objection of the State.  Court takes recess at 11:54.  Trial resumed at 1:29.  Parties present stipulation regarding the bond conditions.  Z.A. appears with Attorney Samuel Benedict.  Z.A. sworn in.  Z.A. invokes his 5th Amendment rights.  Court declares Z.A. unavailable for testimony in this trial.  Jurors recalled at 1:41.  Court reads stipulation.  Exhibit 19 marked, offered and received.  Court advises jurors that the State rests.  Defense calls Detective Thomas Casey to the stand.  Detective Casey sworn in and testified on direct examination, cross examination and redirect.  Exhibit 19 marked.  Jurors excused and court takes recess at 2:38.  Trial resumed at 3:08.  Court conducts colloquy with defendant.  Defendant chooses not to testify.  Defense offers Exhibit 19.  State objects.  Exhibit 19 received by the court over the State's objection.  Defense moves to dismiss.  Court denies motion to dismiss.  Jurors recalled at 3:14.  Jurors advised the defense rests.  State has no rebuttal.  Court declares testimony and evidence closed.  Jurors excused for the evening at 3:18.  Court holds jury instruction conference.  Defense moves to dismiss Count 5.  Court denies defendant's motion.  Court adjourns for the evening at 4:30.
